The correspondence between the orthography and pronunciation is complicated. For example, the offglide {{IPA|/j/}} is usually written as ''i''; however, it may also be represented with ''y''. In addition, in the diphthongs {{IPA|[āj]}} and {{IPA|[āːj]}} the letters ''y'' and ''i'' also indicate the pronunciation of the main vowel: ''ay'' = ''ă'' + {{IPA|/j/}}, ''ai'' = ''a'' + {{IPA|/j/}}. Thus, ''tay'' "hand" is {{IPA|[tāj]}} while ''tai'' "ear" is {{IPA|[tāːj]}}. Similarly, ''u'' and ''o'' indicate different pronunciations of the main vowel: ''au'' = ''ă'' + {{IPA|/w/}}, ''ao'' = ''a'' + {{IPA|/w/}}. Thus, ''thau'' "brass" is {{IPA|[tʰāw]}} while ''thao'' "raw silk" is {{IPA|[tʰāːw]}}.

